item.title: Adding in a command
item.dc:creator: @matzie matzie
item.description:
@matzie wrote:

For the bracket issue, your problem is you pasted in a closing bracket, and have an else if statement after it. (one that uses the same closing bracket as the previous if’s) So you have to remove one of them

[quote=“runescape sucks, post:14, topic:551102”]And another thing, if you are going to use an if else statement,

int a = 3; if(a == 3) { System.out.println("a is 3"); a = 4; return; } else if(a == 4) { System.out.println("a is 4"); a = 5; return; } else { System.out.println("a is "+a); return; }
(Notice the unnecessary return statements)

Would produce this output:

But, if you removed the return statements, you would get the same output.

int a = 3; if(a == 3) { System.out.println("a is 3"); a = 4; } else if(a == 4) { System.out.println("a is 4"); a = 5; } else { System.out.println("a is "+a); }

Output:

Edit:
So in summary, an if else statement checks each if else statement until it finds one that’s true, then it skips the rest of the if else statement and proceeds onto the next part of the code.[/quote]
Great tutorial, but his issue was

if (a == 3) {... } else if (a == 3) {...}
Maybe show why his doesn’t work?

Paradox, If you know at most one condition should match, you use use an else if. Instead of designating an if to 3 mutually exclusive ranges, The program would still have to run all 3 conditions to check if they are true. With an else if you only have to find the one that is true, then stop.

item.title: Adding in a command
item.dc:creator: @Paradox68 Paradox68
item.description:
@Paradox68 wrote:

Brackets can also be found with Notepad++. I know everyone starts somewhere but you guys should know better than to baby him. He won’t learn that way. People shouldn’t come on here looking for exact code to add to their server. We should be able to tell them how to do it while still maintaining a learning environment.

If you think about this case logically, OP the event needs to occur when they click the teleport so the reason your original post had a fault was you posted the case that displays the text. If you navigate to the case where the interface is clicked, you can change the code there using the boolean isDonator to check on click whether the player has the specified rank. Hopefully you understand the logistics of coding it in such a way.

You could use multiple methods to efficiently code this specific action.
a.) switch statement

[code]public void test() {
boolean abc = false;
switch (abc) {
case true:
sM(“Hi”);
return;

	sM("Bye");  //this will only be called if case true is not called, due to the return statement.
}

}
[/code]

b.) Else if

public void test() {
boolean abc = false;
	if (abc == true) {
		sM("Hi");
		return;
       } else {
		sM("Bye");
       }
}

c.) Multiple if

public void test() {
int level = misc.random(50);
          if (level < 25) {
                sM("Low");
          }
          if (level >= 25 && level < 40) {
                sM("Medium");
          }
          if (level >= 40) {
               sM("high");
          }
}
